#Bivariate
# Correlation between features in graphical representation so below is function for that
def plot_corr(df, size=11):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')

plot_corr(csv)

In [81]:
#Calculate Accuracy , Precisison , Recall and F1  Score
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, recall_score, roc_auc_score, precision_score,roc_curve, auc,f1_score
from matplotlib import pyplot

#Accuracy
test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict,1)
print('Accuracy is : {} %'.format(test_accuracy*100))

#Precision
precision = precision_score(y_test, y_predict)
print('Precision is : {}'.format(precision))

#Recall
recall = recall_score(y_test, y_predict)
print('Recall is : {}'.format(recall))


#F1 score
F1 = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
print('F1 Score is : {}'.format(F1))



#ROC Curve
# predict probabilities for ROC curve to get the positive outcome only
lr_probs = model.predict_proba(x_test)
lr_probs = lr_probs[:, 1]


#AUC score
lr_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_probs)
# summarize scores
print('Logistic: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (lr_auc))

# calculate roc curves
lr_fpr, lr_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, lr_probs)

# plot the roc curve for the model
pyplot.figure()
pyplot.plot(lr_fpr, lr_tpr, marker='.', label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc)
pyplot.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
pyplot.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
pyplot.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
# axis labels
pyplot.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
pyplot.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
pyplot.title('ROC Curve for the model')
# show the legend
pyplot.legend()
pyplot.savefig('Log_ROC')
# show the plot
pyplot.show()

5. Give your reasoning on how can the model perform better?¶

In [103]:
# One way to improve the model better is to try different threshold values to improve the F1 and ROC AUC score
model = LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear")
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

#predict  the number of a customers buying personal loanson test
y_predict = model.predict(x_test)

threshold_list = [0.05,0.1,0.15,0.2,0.25,0.3,0.35,0.4,0.45,0.5,0.55,0.6,0.65,.7,.75,.8,.85,.9,.95,.99]
cols = ['Threshold','Accuracy','ROC AUC score','F1 Score']
lst=[]
for i in threshold_list:

    # classify the predicated probabilities with given threshold to get positive outcome accordingly
    y_preds = np.where(model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1] > i, 1, 0)
   
    # calculate Accuracy Score as per the threshold
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test,y_preds,1)
    
    print('Testing accuracy with Threshold: {} is : {}'.format(i,test_accuracy))
    
    #AUC score
    lr_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_preds)
    
    print('ROC AUC score with Threshold: {} is : {}'.format(i,lr_auc))
    
    #F1 score
    F1=f1_score(y_test, y_preds, zero_division=1)
    
    
    print('F1 Score is with Threshold: {} is : {}'.format(i,F1))
    
    
    print('===========================================================')
    
    lst.append([i,test_accuracy,lr_auc,F1])
   
    
df = pd.DataFrame(lst, columns=cols)
df.to_csv("Threshold_Matrix.csv")
    
    
#Conclusion: From the below given matrix , the model performs the best with Threshold 0.4 , with highest F1 score
# ( better than threshold   0.5):

6. Give Business understanding of your model?¶

1) This is a business with a goal to maximize the number of customers accepting personal loans.¶
2) The goal comes under the category of reverse churn prediction, where we want more people to accept personal loans. Therefore in this case, False Positives ( people who where expected to accept personal loan but they do not) would be more costly in terms of the campaign money spent as per the prediction from the given model.¶
3)Therefore this business model should concentrate on higher precision than recall.¶
In [106]:
